# Router-on-a-Stick and DHCP Troubleshooting

## Problem Faced

After configuring VLANs, trunking, and EtherChannel, PCs were still unable to receive IP addresses automatically through DHCP.

The PCs were getting:

```bash id="b3u7pz"
169.254.x.x
```

This indicated that DHCP was failing.

---

# Initial Symptoms

While checking the router interfaces using:

```bash id="w9q2er"
show ip interface brief
```

The output showed:

```bash id="m5k1xt"
FastEthernet0/0        up      down
FastEthernet0/0.10     up      down
FastEthernet0/0.20     up      down
FastEthernet0/0.30     up      down
FastEthernet0/0.40     up      down
```

This meant:

* Physical interface status was UP
* Protocol status was DOWN
* VLAN communication was failing

As a result:

* DHCP requests were not reaching the router
* Inter-VLAN communication was not working

---

# Root Cause Analysis

The issue happened because Router-on-a-Stick was configured on the WRONG interface.

The router cable was actually connected to:

```bash id="t8v4qp"
FastEthernet0/1
```

But subinterfaces were mistakenly configured on:

```bash id="r2m9kx"
FastEthernet0/0
```

Because of this mismatch:

* Router subinterfaces stayed down
* VLAN tagging failed
* DHCP broadcasts could not pass through

---

# Troubleshooting Process

## Step 1 — Verified Active Router Interface

Used command:

```bash id="x4n7tw"
show ip interface brief
```

This helped identify:

* Active connected interface
* Interface status
* Protocol status

The correct working interface was:

```bash id="v1q8mz"
FastEthernet0/1
```

---

# Step 2 — Removed Wrong Subinterfaces

Removed incorrect configurations from FastEthernet0/0:

```bash id="d7m2qp"
configure terminal
no interface fa0/0.10
no interface fa0/0.20
no interface fa0/0.30
no interface fa0/0.40
```

---

# Step 3 — Configured Correct Router-on-a-Stick Interface

Configured subinterfaces on the correct interface:

```bash id="g5v9kr"
interface fa0/1
no shutdown
```

---

# VLAN 10 Configuration

```bash id="p3m8tx"
interface fa0/1.10
encapsulation dot1Q 10
ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0
```

---

# VLAN 20 Configuration

```bash id="u6q1mw"
interface fa0/1.20
encapsulation dot1Q 20
ip address 192.168.20.1 255.255.255.0
```

---

# VLAN 30 Configuration

```bash id="y2v7np"
interface fa0/1.30
encapsulation dot1Q 30
ip address 192.168.30.1 255.255.255.0
```

---

# VLAN 40 Configuration

```bash id="c8m4qz"
interface fa0/1.40
encapsulation dot1Q 40
ip address 192.168.40.1 255.255.255.0
```

---

# Step 4 — Configured Trunk on Switch Port

The switch port connected to the router was configured as trunk:

```bash id="n4v8xt"
interface fa0/24
switchport mode trunk
```

This allowed VLAN traffic to pass between:

* Switch
* Router

---

# Step 5 — Verification

After correcting the interface configuration:

```bash id="z7q2mr"
show ip interface brief
```

Now showed:

```bash id="m1v5kp"
FastEthernet0/1.10     up     up
FastEthernet0/1.20     up     up
FastEthernet0/1.30     up     up
FastEthernet0/1.40     up     up
```

This confirmed:

* Router-on-a-Stick was functioning correctly
* VLAN tagging was operational
* Inter-VLAN routing was active

---

# DHCP Problem

Even after Router-on-a-Stick started working, PCs still failed to obtain IP addresses.

---

# Root Cause

Only excluded addresses were configured:

```bash id="u3m9qx"
ip dhcp excluded-address 192.168.10.1
ip dhcp excluded-address 192.168.20.1
ip dhcp excluded-address 192.168.30.1
ip dhcp excluded-address 192.168.40.1
```

But actual DHCP pools were missing.

Without DHCP pools:

* Router had no IP ranges to assign
* PCs continued receiving APIPA addresses (`169.254.x.x`)

---

# DHCP Solution

Configured DHCP pools for each VLAN.

---

# VLAN10 DHCP Pool

```bash id="x8q4nt"
ip dhcp pool VLAN10
network 192.168.10.0 255.255.255.0
default-router 192.168.10.1
dns-server 8.8.8.8
```

---

# VLAN20 DHCP Pool

```bash id="k2v7mp"
ip dhcp pool VLAN20
network 192.168.20.0 255.255.255.0
default-router 192.168.20.1
dns-server 8.8.8.8
```

---

# VLAN30 DHCP Pool

```bash id="w5m1qz"
ip dhcp pool VLAN30
network 192.168.30.0 255.255.255.0
default-router 192.168.30.1
dns-server 8.8.8.8
```

---

# VLAN40 DHCP Pool

```bash id="n9v3kr"
ip dhcp pool VLAN40
network 192.168.40.0 255.255.255.0
default-router 192.168.40.1
dns-server 8.8.8.8
```

---

# Final Verification

After configuring DHCP pools:

* PCs successfully received IP addresses
* Inter-VLAN communication worked
* Default gateways were assigned automatically

Verification command:

```bash id="q4m8tx"
show ip dhcp binding
```

Successfully displayed dynamically assigned IP addresses.

